  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained funds appear legitimate by passing them through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. It is universally recognized as a criminal activity because it enables other serious crimes, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud, by allowing perpetrators to use the proceeds of their illegal activities without detection.\n\nMost countries have enacted specific laws and regulations to combat money laundering. These laws typically require financial institutions and other entities to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities, conduct customer due diligence, and maintain records. International organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), have also established global standards and recommendations to help countries develop and enforce effective anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is widely and unequivocally recognized as illegal, and efforts to combat it are a key focus of law enforcement and regulatory agencies worldwide.",
